Jul 30 2007 	All the basics in a great location at a great price	All the basics are here: cleanliness, 100% functional bathroom (with plenty of sink-area counter space stocked with soaps, shampoo, conditioner, mouth wash), functioning electrical outlets and appliances, tv with remote, mini-refrigerator, clock radio, picture over the bed, air conditioner, comfortable bed, front desk staff who were helpful (and didn't have long lines), tasty breads for complimentary breakfast. I arrived at 11 am (before my room was ready)--but storing my bag was no problem: they took it right away and (in the afternoon) retrieved it very quickly, offering it to me with a ready smile.Location was great--roughly a ten-minute walk to Penn Station along Seventh Avenue. The 23rd Street station on the Seventh Avenue Subway was right at the corner.And . . . would you believe I got a room rate of $99 (plus tax)?Keep in mind that this was not a room for picky travelers. When I booked it, the clerk warned me that it was next to the elevators. I didn't hear any noise from the elevators (and the room was very quiet in general), but the room (#519) did have an unusual shape to accommodate the space for the elevators. The room didn't seem large, but I didn't feel cramped. Just inside the room is a conventional (but small) bathroom and an alcove for the apparently queen-size bed. As you keep walking farther into the room, you have a corridor-like extension (maybe 4 feet wide, roughly). Walk down that for roughly 10 feet, and you get to the closet. Just beyond the closet is a small window. The view is just part of the hotel and some nearby buildings--not very impressive. The air conditioner was a bit noisy--but I've experienced that problem elsewhere and, despite it, I slept well.Also, I noticed some scuff marks on the walls. In the lobby, the covering on the couch had some tears.For me, those issues were not important. I didn't visit Manhattan in order to be a room inspector. I wanted a place to stay that was conveniently located, comfortable, functional, and clean--with staff that would facilitate my arrival and departure.	
Jul 22 2007 	Couldn't Recover from Problems	We've stayed at the Chelsea Savoy three times prior to our stay in July of 2007, and it always worked fine. It's a clean, safe, decent-sized room hotel in Chelsea. This time, we booked the room for a non-smoking king at $195 a night. That's a great price for NYC, and especially in a good location.However, upon getting to the room, we started having problems. As other travelers have noted, they've recently changed the carpet, and the smell is not at all subtle (at least on the 2nd floor it's not.) You do get used to the smell, but it smells none the less. And, for those with a good sense of smell, it would likely be almost too strong to deal with. The next issue we had was that our air conditioner didn't work. They sent the maintenance guy up to look at it. All he did was dial the temp down to 60deg and say it was &quot;Work OK.&quot; Nevermind the error code that was flashing on the display, or that 60deg is too cold to tolerate. They couldn't move us, because there were no other rooms in the hotel. Finally, the staff just didn't care - at all. Yes, I realize it's New York, and we're not paying for a 4-star hotel, but they could at least show some shred of empathy, or apologize, but nope! SO, after all this, we're done with the Savoy. IF you get a room that has no problems, and isn't right on the corner of 23rd and 7th, then you'll be a lucky guest. But, if your room stinks, or has an issue, you'll realize it's time to check out somewhere else...Good luck!	
